<p>Gunmen opened fire at a soccer field in Salamanca, in Mexico’s violence-hit state of Guanajuato, killing 11 people and injuring 12, according to local officials and multiple news reports. The shooting followed a match and occurred in an area where criminal groups have competed for control, underscoring how community events can be caught up in broader cartel-linked violence. Local authorities described the attack as part of a wider surge in insecurity in the city and appealed for greater federal support to curb violence.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/vbGt2qDdKl1roFI12oeRBxMdo3bTmJbOjI0OQ3hnJm5zsL9fACivoUQgaD4Ou9TuJ1qE0cWaPPRbkZfEsX7XQZByxfnkkM_sPSW_Xho8augjjiEeCJRPWW7TPlZcpL_0ZSM1Qs16t8cIXu-nMUP0U23khonbPmELjYzvPFs3vLMVX9UpUXR7GMX7ALO02RtqTo4Qt5ED_EqrwkiK' alt='Mexican National Guard members at the scene where 11 people were killed in Salamanca, Mexico, on Sunday.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Mayor’s appeal: Salamanca’s mayor publicly asked President Claudia Sheinbaum for help, saying the city is facing a “crime wave”.</li><li>Broader violence: In the same town, authorities also found four bags containing human remains on the night of Jan. 24, highlighting a wider pattern of brutality beyond the stadium attack.</li><li>Security presence: Mexican National Guard personnel were reported at the scene as authorities secured the area and responded to the incident.</li><li>Political backdrop: The attack came as Mexico’s government has sought to demonstrate to Washington that it is taking action against criminal groups.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Salamanca city government: City officials framed the shooting as part of a broader local spike in violence and urged stronger federal intervention to restore security. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/mexico-gunmen-kill-11-at-soccer-field-in-salamanca/a-75655738'>DW</a>)</li><li>Mexican federal government (security posture): Federal authorities have been seeking to show the United States that Mexico is combating criminal organizations, a context highlighted as the country confronts continued violence. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/26/world/americas/mexico-shooting-salamanca-cartels.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/26/world/americas/mexico-shooting-salamanca-cartels.html'>Gunmen Kill 11 After Soccer Match in Mexico</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/mexico-shooting-updates-monday-january-26/article70552004.ece'>Gunmen open fire at soccer field in central Mexico, killing 11 and wounding 12</a> - thehindu.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/mexico-gunmen-kill-11-at-soccer-field-in-salamanca/a-75655738'>Mexico: Gunmen kill 11 at soccer field in Salamanca</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/11-dead-12-more-wounded-in-armed-attack-at-soccer-field-in-central-mexico'>11 dead, 12 wounded in armed attack at football field in central Mexico</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.proceso.com.mx/nacional/estados/2026/1/25/masacre-en-campo-de-futbol-de-salamanca-guanajuato-comando-asesina-11-personas-367226.html'>Eleven people are killed and 12 more injured in a mass shooting during a football match in Salamanca, Guanajuato, Mexico.</a> - proceso.com.mx</li></ul>